TONIGHT ON THE CBS EVENING NEWS
<http://www.cbsnews.com/sections/eveningnews/main3420.shtml>=20

Here's an early look at what we are working on from Anchor and Managing
Editor, Katie Couric...=20

Hi everyone,=20

This morning, the Rutgers women's basketball team spoke up about
controversial comments made about them by radio host Don Imus. Their
coach slammed what she called "racist and sexist remarks that are
deplorable, despicable and unconscionable." The team captain said Imus
had stolen "a moment of pure grace" from the athletes. Nancy Cordes will
have the story and Richard Schlesinger will put the Imus controversy in
perspective with a report on racism in America.=20

On Capitol Hill, momentum is building up to a likely clash over
stem-cell research. As dual bills that would provide public funding for
research using human embryos move through Congress, the White House says
that President Bush's veto pen is ready for whatever form of the
legislation hits his desk. Sharyl Attkisson will have that story.=20

And Dr. Jon LaPook will look at one of the potential uses for
stem-cells: to help cure type 1 diabetes. The Journal of the American
Medical Association reported that stem cells taken from the blood of a
small sample of diabetes patients have helped the patients' immune
systems go months, and even years, without insulin. Fourteen out of the
15 patients studied saw marked improvement in their diabetes, showing a
glimmer of hope for a cure.=20

In other health news, researchers reported last night that the
fastest-growing group of obese people in the United States are those 100
pounds or more overweight. These people are known as "severely obese."
The proportion of Americans fitting that description grew by an
astonishing 50 percent between 2000 and 2005.  Kelly Cobiella will bring
us this report.=20

For two years Army Specialist Mario Lozano has agonized about taking the
life of an Italian secret agent while manning a roadblock on Iraq's most
dangerous highway. Now, as he awaits trial in Italy for the death of
Nicola Calipari, Lozano shares details of the shooting with our chief
foreign correspondent Lara Logan.=20

I hope you'll join us. Katie=20

For more on the stories noted above, please click on the following
links:=20

Rutgers Team: Angry, Disgusted At Imus=20
Click Here
<http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/04/10/national/main2666824.shtml>=20=
=20

Bush Promises Veto On Stem Cell Bill=20
Click Here
<http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/04/10/politics/main2667460.shtml>=20=
=20

And here's an early look at one of the stories we are working on for
Wednesday's broadcast of the CBS Evening News:=20

Fighting in Afghanistan between NATO forces and the Taliban is
intensifying with the arrival of spring, and our Lara Logan is in the
thick of it. So that story and much more, Wednesday night, on the CBS
Evening News.=20

If you would like more information on the broadcast, please click on the
following address and e-mail us:=20
evening@cbsnews.com <mailto:evening@cbsnews.com>=20

